<section xml:id="sec-ula-exercises-2-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>PROTEUS ULA Exercises - Section 2.1-2.2</title>
    <exercise component="proteus" label="ula_proteus_Section_2_2_Linear_Combinations_v1">
      <title>Checking whether a vector is a linear combination of other vectors</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Explain how you would determine whether a given vector <m>\vvec</m> in <m>\real^n</m> 
          is a linear combination of a given set of vectors <m>\xvec_1</m>, <m>\xvec_2</m>, <m>\xvec_3</m> 
          in <m>\real^n</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>

    <exercise component="proteus" label="ula_proteus_Section_2_2_Linear_Combinations2_v1">
      <title>Write a vector as a linear combination of other vectors in three ways</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Express the vector <m>\vvec =\threevec{8}{-7}{-17} </m> as a linear combination of
          <m> \xvec_1= \threevec1{-1}2,
          \xvec_2 = \threevec{-1}21,
          \xvec_3 = \threevec3{-2}{-7}</m>
          in three different ways. Explain how you arrived at your three different expressions. </p>
        </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>

    <exercise component="proteus" label="ula_proteus_Section_2_2_Linear_Combinations3_v1">
      <title>The connection between linear combinations and matrix multiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, <m>\vvec_3</m> 
          are vectors in <m>\real^3</m>, and let 
          <m>A=\left[ \begin{array}{ccc} \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \vvec_3\end{array}\right]</m>.  
          Suppose that a solution to 
          <m>A\xvec= \threevec{11}{5}{-7} </m> 
          is given by <m>\xvec = \threevec4{-1}2</m>.
          Find constants <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m>, and <m>c_3</m> with
          <me>c_1 \vvec_1 + c_2 \vvec_2 + c_3\vvec_3 = 
          \threevec{11}{5}{-7}</me>.
          Explain your thinking.</p>
        </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>

</section>